<h2 id="html"><strong>HTML</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>In addition to the HTTP headers that include status codes, the bits representing an image or website will be sent to you</li>
  <li>The language that builds websites is HTML (Hypertext Markup Language)
    <ul>
      <li>Sent as a response for a request for a web page</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>HTML isnâ€™t a programming language but rather a markup language
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Allows you to format, but doesnâ€™t have control flow such as loops and conditions</p>

        <div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  <span class="cp">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</span>

  <span class="nt">&lt;html</span> <span class="na">lang=</span><span class="s">"en"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;title&gt;</span>hello, world<span class="nt">&lt;/title&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;body&gt;</span>
          hello, world
      <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div>        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>This is html for a webpage that says â€œhello, worldâ€</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>To implement webpages, you need to write HTML
    <ul>
      <li>Editors like Atom and Sublime Text exist to help write HTML
        <ul>
          <li>Ultimately, all you need is a computer, a keyboard, and some way of typing out text!</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</code>
    <ul>
      <li>Lets the browser know the following file is written in HTML 5</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;html lang="en"&gt;</code>
    <ul>
      <li>Specifies that the webpage is written in English</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;</code>
    <ul>
      <li>Example of open and close tags</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>First tag opened is the last tag closed
    <ul>
      <li>HTML is a tag-based markup language
        <ul>
          <li>Tags have attributes</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Standard extension for a webpage is .html</li>
  <li>David clicks the hello.html file and loads the page
    <ul>
      <li>In the top corner of the browser tab is the title
        <ul>
          <li>This comes from theÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">head</code></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>TheÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">body</code>Â contains 99% of the webpageâ€™s content</li>
      <li>This page is a local document, so the address is where David saved it
        <ul>
          <li>Not on a web server, so no one else can access it</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>There are web hosts to serve up websites we write
    <ul>
      <li>We can also buy our own domain name</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

