</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">action="https://www.google.com/search" method="get"</code>Â means â€œget me https://www.google.com/searchâ€</li>
  <li>Inside the form, we can haveÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;input/&gt;</code>Â tags
    <ul>
      <li>These can have name, type, value, and text attributes</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>This implementation punts the searching to Google</li>
  <li>The browser uses the HTML form to assemble a URL
    <ul>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">https://www.google.com/search?q=cats</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">?</code>Â in the URL means â€œHey Server! Here comes my HTTP parameters!â€
    <ul>
      <li>A URL may have multiple parameters separated byÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&amp;</code></li>
