</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>Here, insideÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">body</code>, we have three tags:Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;header&gt;&lt;/header&gt;</code>,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;main&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</code>, andÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;footer&gt;&lt;/footer&gt;</code>
    <ul>
      <li>They include style attributes written in CSS
        <ul>
          <li>These are written as key-value pairs</li>
          <li>In CSS, there is a property calledÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">font-size</code>
            <ul>
              <li>CSS supportsÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">small</code>,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">medium</code>,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">large</code>, and exact sizes such asÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">16px</code></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">text-align: center;</code>Â centers the text</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>This example has some redundancy</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="dom"><strong>DOM</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>CSS supports the notion of a hierarchy
    <ul>
      <li>Rectangles here represent HTML tags or elements</li>
      <li>Ovals represent text values</li>
      <li>This is called a tree in Computer Science, much like a family tree</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>When a browser receives a webpage, it builds a tree-like data structure in your computerâ€™s RAM</li>
  <li>Thus, in this caseÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">header</code>,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main</code>, andÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">footer</code>Â are all child nodes of of the parent nodeÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">body</code></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="css1html"><strong>css1.html</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>We can put theÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">text-align: center;</code>Â attribute on theÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">body</code>Â element so it will pass it on to its children (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">header</code>,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main</code>, andÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">footer</code>)</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="cp">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</span>

<span class="nt">&lt;html</span> <span class="na">lang=</span><span class="s">"en"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;title&gt;</span>css1<span class="nt">&lt;/title&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;body</span> <span class="na">style=</span><span class="s">"text-align: center;"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;header</span> <span class="na">style=</span><span class="s">"font-size: large;"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
            Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;main</span> <span class="na">style=</span><span class="s">"font-size: medium;"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
            Welcome to my home page!
        <span class="nt">&lt;/main&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;footer</span> <span class="na">style=</span><span class="s">"font-size: small;"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
            Copyright <span class="ni">&amp;%169;</span> Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/footer&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>This is better design as we can change all the text alignment at once</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="css2html"><strong>css2.html</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>Combining HTML and CSS is generally frowned upon</li>
  <li>Makes it hard to collaborate
    <ul>
      <li>One person can work on content (HTML)</li>
      <li>The other on style (CSS)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  <span class="cp">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</span>

  <span class="nt">&lt;html</span> <span class="na">lang=</span><span class="s">"en"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;style&gt;</span>

              <span class="nc">.centered</span>
              <span class="p">{</span>
                  <span class="nl">text-align</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">center</span><span class="p">;</span>
              <span class="p">}</span>

              <span class="nc">.large</span>
              <span class="p">{</span>
                  <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">large</span><span class="p">;</span>
              <span class="p">}</span>

              <span class="nc">.medium</span>
              <span class="p">{</span>
                  <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">medium</span><span class="p">;</span>
              <span class="p">}</span>

              <span class="nc">.small</span>
              <span class="p">{</span>
                  <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">small</span><span class="p">;</span>
              <span class="p">}</span>

          <span class="nt">&lt;/style&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;title&gt;</span>css2<span class="nt">&lt;/title&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;body</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"centered"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;header</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"large"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
              Bui Quang Bao
          <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;main</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"medium"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
              Welcome to my home page!
          <span class="nt">&lt;/main&gt;</span>
          <span class="nt">&lt;footer</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"small"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
              Copyright <span class="ni">&amp;%169;</span> Bui Quang Bao
          <span class="nt">&lt;/footer&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div>    </div>

    <ul>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;style&gt;</code>Â can be a tag as well as an attribute</li>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.centered</code>Â defines a class namedÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">centered</code>
        <ul>
          <li>Anything with this class with have the style attributeÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">text-align: center;</code></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="css3html"><strong>css3.html</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>We can even get rid of class attributes to further separate style from content</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="cp">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</span>

<span class="nt">&lt;html</span> <span class="na">lang=</span><span class="s">"en"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;style&gt;</span>

            <span class="nt">body</span>
            <span class="p">{</span>
                <span class="nl">text-align</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">center</span><span class="p">;</span>
            <span class="p">}</span>

            <span class="nt">header</span>
            <span class="p">{</span>
                <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">large</span><span class="p">;</span>
            <span class="p">}</span>

            <span class="nt">main</span>
            <span class="p">{</span>
                <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">medium</span><span class="p">;</span>
            <span class="p">}</span>

            <span class="nt">footer</span>
            <span class="p">{</span>
                <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">small</span><span class="p">;</span>
            <span class="p">}</span>

        <span class="nt">&lt;/style&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;title&gt;</span>css3<span class="nt">&lt;/title&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;body&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;header&gt;</span>
            Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;main&gt;</span>
            Welcome to my home page!
        <span class="nt">&lt;/main&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;footer&gt;</span>
            Copyright <span class="ni">&amp;%169;</span> Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/footer&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>We can also give the tags CSS directly</li>
  <li>Will look identical, but better design</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="css4html"><strong>css4.html</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>What if we remove the style altogether and store it elsewhere?</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="cp">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</span>

<span class="nt">&lt;html</span> <span class="na">lang=</span><span class="s">"en"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;link</span> <span class="na">href=</span><span class="s">"css4.css"</span> <span class="na">rel=</span><span class="s">"stylesheet"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;title&gt;</span>css4<span class="nt">&lt;/title&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;body&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;header&gt;</span>
            Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;main&gt;</span>
            Welcome to my home page!
        <span class="nt">&lt;/main&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;footer&gt;</span>
            Copyright <span class="ni">&amp;%169;</span> Bui Quang Bao
        <span class="nt">&lt;/footer&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>We have boiled the html down to its essence
    <ul>
      <li>No usage of style tags</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Note theÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;link/&gt;</code>Â tag with aÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">href</code>Â attribute ofÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">css4.css</code>Â and aÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">rel</code>Â (relationship) attribute ofÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">stylesheet</code>
    <ul>
      <li>This says â€œHey Browser! Please link my stylesheet css4.css to this page!â€</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>In the same directory, we will have this stylesheet</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-css highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">body</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">text-align</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">center</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="nt">header</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">large</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="nt">main</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">medium</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="nt">footer</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">small</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>We have factored out the style to its own file
    <ul>
      <li>Easier for collaboration and sharing</li>
      <li>Can use on multiple html pages</li>
      <li>Can create different themes</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="closing-thoughts"><strong>Closing Thoughts</strong></h2>

<ul>
  <li>Web development is about writing code
    <ul>
      <li>Specifically, HTML, which builds the structure of a webpage</li>
      <li>CSS allows us to fine tune the webpageâ€™s aesthetics</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>You can use these building blocks to further learn about web development on your own!</li>
  <li>The underlying concepts are more important than details
    <ul>
      <li>A webpage is nothing more than a text file written in HTML, CSS, and maybe some JavaScript
        <ul>
          <li>This file can be uploaded to a server to put on the internet
            <ul>
              <li>You can sign up for a web host with data centers</li>
              <li>All your files will go in a folder on the server so that the webpage can be accessed on the internet</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>You can also buy a domain name and configure it to point to the web host</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>These building blocks are what allow you to put your content on the internet!</li>
</ul>
